  "id": "county-in-coverage-note",
  "person": "(coverage)",
  "role": "Indiana sheriffs \u2014 coverage note",
  "jurisdiction": "Indiana",
  "branch": "law_enforcement",
  "level": "county",
  "status": "incumbent",
  "party": "",
  "as_of": "2026-07-04",
  "source_url": "https://www.indianasheriffs.org/",
  "source_dataset": "county_sheriffs",
  "note": "All 92 counties enumerated from the official Indiana Sheriffs directory (in.gov/sheriffs machine-readable roster) as the backbone. Verified a representative sample against county sheriff sites/Ballotpedia/local news: Marion (Forestal, D), Lake (Martinez, D), Allen (Hershberger, R), St. Joseph (Grzegorek, D), Porter (Balon, R), Vanderburgh (Robinson, D), Tippecanoe (Goldsmith, D), Monroe (Marte, D), plus ~16 more. Two mid-term corrections applied where the roster was stale: Vigo \u2014 Derek Fell (D) appointed Aug 2024 after Sheriff John Plasse died in office July 24, 2024; Clinton \u2014 Brendon Bright (R) sworn in May 23, 2026 via GOP caucus after Sheriff Richard Kelly resigned on a guilty plea. Note Dubois \u2014 Tom Kleinhelter remains the elected sheriff despite relinquishing law-enforcement certification (elected constitutional office; faces pending charges). Indiana sheriffs are partisan-elected to 4-year terms with a strict two-term limit; the major term-limit turnover cohort is 2026 (many 2-term incumbents \u2014 Forestal/Marion, Quakenbush/Hamilton, Grzegorek/St. Joseph, Burgess/Johnson, Wilder/Warrick \u2014 are term-limited, with successors elected Nov 2026 and seated Jan 2027), so most roster names remain the sitting incumbents on 2026-07-04. Party evidenced for 24 counties (Republican=17, Democratic=7); left blank for 68 where not individually verified \u2014 Indiana skews Republican but party was not assumed. Counts: 92 counties + 1 coverage note = 93 objects."
 }
